# Hexagonal Architecture Port/Adapter Skill

## Purpose
Guide an AI agent through defining ports (interfaces) and implementing adapters following Hexagonal Architecture (Ports & Adapters).

## Sections to Generate

### When to Use This Skill
Describe scenarios: integrating external services, defining repository contracts, creating API clients, implementing database access, adding messaging adapters.

### Port Design
- Ports are interfaces defined in the domain layer
- Driven ports (inbound): define how the application is used (use case interfaces)
- Driving ports (outbound): define what the application needs (repository, gateway, notifier interfaces)
- Name ports by domain intent, not technology (OrderRepository, not PostgresOrderStore)

### Adapter Implementation
Step-by-step:
1. Identify the domain need (what capability is required?)
2. Define the port interface in domain layer with domain types
3. Implement the adapter in infrastructure layer
4. Register adapter in composition root via dependency injection
5. Write adapter-specific tests (integration tests with real dependencies or testcontainers)

### Primary vs Secondary Adapters
- Primary (driving): HTTP handlers, CLI commands, gRPC services, message consumers — they call the application
- Secondary (driven): database repos, API clients, email senders, queue publishers — the application calls them
- Both implement interfaces; primary adapters call use case ports, secondary adapters implement outbound ports

### Testing Strategy
- Domain logic: unit tests with mock adapters
- Adapters: integration tests against real infrastructure (testcontainers, in-memory databases)
- Ports: contract tests to verify adapter compliance

### Anti-patterns to Avoid
- Technology-specific types in port interfaces (sql.DB, http.Request in domain)
- Adapter logic leaking into domain
- Skipping the port and coupling domain directly to infrastructure
- One giant port interface (split by cohesive capability)

### Verification
How to validate correct port/adapter implementation: domain has zero infrastructure imports, adapters are swappable, tests run without external dependencies.
